<Layout
  title="About"
  description="What the Macondo Atlas is, how it was made, and where its words come from."
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <p class="eyebrow">Colophon</p>
    <h1>About this atlas</h1>
  </header>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      The Macondo Atlas is a reader's companion to <em>One Hundred Years of Solitude</em> by
      Gabriel García Márquez (1967), read here in Gregory Rabassa's 1970 English
      translation. It exists to solve the book's one famous difficulty — seven generations
      sharing two names — and to make visible what the novel keeps insisting: that time in
      Macondo is a circle, and every life rhymes with another.
    </p>
    <p>
      Everything on this site — the summaries, the dossiers, the timeline, the map, the
      family tree — is original descriptive and analytical writing. Brief quotations from
      the Rabassa translation appear with attribution, in the spirit of fair use. The novel
      itself is not reproduced here, and this atlas is no substitute for it: read the book.
    </p>
    <p>
      The color system encodes the family's own logic. García Márquez's narrator observes
      that while the Aurelianos were withdrawn but lucid, the José Arcadios were impulsive
      and enterprising, and both were marked with a tragic sign. Blue for the Aurelianos,
      red for the José Arcadios, gold for the matriarchs who outlast them all, violet for
      the Remedios line, green for everyone the century swept in.
    </p>
    <p>
      Built with Astro and D3, typeset in Fraunces, Newsreader, and Archivo. Source on
      <a href="https://github.com/ewijaya/macondo-interactive">GitHub</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
